    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> I don't think a pip-installable option can work without having people do %load_ext install_ext first, and that gets a bit ridiculous.\r\n\r\nFair point. \r\n\r\n> From the relative lack of issues complaining that we broke things, we got away with this, but I think it was a sadly cavalier attitude to extension authors to remove functionality. It's a long way from Linux's don't break userspace.\r\n\r\nWe are a relatively fast moving project and we do have better backward compat and deprecation cycle than most. Also (hum.. Python 2 ... hum). \r\n\r\n\r\n> I'll fudge it on the wiki page :(\r\n\r\nThanks.\r\n\r\nSpeaking of \"Don't break user space\" I'm working on a tool to compare 2 versions of a python package and warn (fail?) when API is not backward compatible. Think roughly walking object hierarchy and dumping function signature. I'm mostly interested to catch the accidental positional-argument-renaming mistakes. I can ping you once I push a not too ugly version. "
  },
