    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> Regarding the tool, I'd say the important thing is to emphasise that getting a green light from the tool does not mean you're 100% backwards compatible: what happens inside the functions matters as well as the function signature, and that's much harder for a tool to check.\r\n\r\nYes, definitively. I'm also not looking at types in the  signature. I'm looking at something that has as little false negative. Focusing for now on non intentional change of function signature (I catched a few in matplotlib 1.5->2.0 but it's too late now). And also something that can give me a list of change to review. \r\n\r\nA change can easily sneak through multiple PRs, as you may think a change had not been released yet and bring modification to APIs where you should not.\r\n\r\nIt does not of course remove work from the reviewer (I don't want to be without a job ðŸ˜„  )"
